				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Well, there's the pharmacist's creed, for one thing:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">
<br />
I hold my patients' interests above all others.
<br />

<br />
I take responsibility for my patients' medication-related needs.
<br />

<br />
I ensure that my patients' medications are the most appropriate, the most effective available, the safest possible, and are used correctly.
<br />

<br />
I identify, resolve, and prevent medication-related problems that may interfere with the goals of therapy.
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
But that aside, suppose the pharmacist had been a Christian Scientist and refused to give someone their seizure or asthma medication? Or a Scientologist who refused to give someone their antidepressants?
<br />

<br />
Employers can't discriminate on the basis of religion. This places pharmacies in the position of having to. 
<br />

<br />
And what about Muslims, Jews, and Hindis who work in supermarkets or restaurants that sell pork and beef and shellfish? Should they be able to decide what you're allowed to buy or order? ("No, I'm sorry, I can't sell you a steak because it's against my religion. No, fuck you and your Atkins.")<br />_________________<br />Bangzoom
<br />
65th Ranger of Doomnation
<br />
Veteran Crew Through and Through</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
