				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I believe that a company (or the state for licensing purposes) can't discriminate based on the religious tennets of a person. Ergo, they can't say those pesky CSM or CS can't be pharmacists because they can't fill certain types of scripts.
<br />

<br />
I would imaging that gets handled in the pharmacy classes and internships, where you have to fill those types of scripts to be certified.  And damned if you aren't certified from a school, you can't take the boards and be a pharmacist.  <img src="images/smiles/icon_twisted.gif" alt="icon_twisted.gif" border="0" /> 
<br />

<br />
The state, the licensing organization for pharmacists, should reprimand him, he violated the oath he took and the document they sign for their license.  Not so much that he didn't dispense the drugs, but because he refused to release the script.  I think a 30 day suspension isn't excessive and warranted.  I also think the manager over the pharmacy should have to face disciplinary action within the company.  BC is so common these days that he should have had contengency plan in the event that someone came into the store requesting them.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
