				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The original case I remember was whether a gas station corporation could remove someone  from a contract because they refused to open a store on the Sabbath.  Most of the legal opinions I've seen online religious tolerance and employment boil down to "It depends."
<br />

<br />
The statement that summed it up most closely was "unless the employer demonstrates that accommodation would result in undue hardship on the conduct of its business", an accomodation should be made.
<br />

<br />
There seem to be a couple dozen shades of grey available on this one.  Undoubtedly, the legal types can correct me if I'm wrong.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
