			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">There are a couple of cases that talk about having to work on the sabbath.  They all have to do the with the free exercise clause and when the state could deny unemployment benefits.  The old (sherbert v. verner) rule was that no law could be made that unduly burdened religion.  That rule was abandoned in the 90s (smith v. washington employment division- native american state drug rehabilitation worker fired for smoking peyote).  The new rule is that a state may make any law that burdens religion as long as the law is not intentionally trying to stop that religious practice and the law is a law of general applicability...  that is how the free exercise clause is applied...
<br />
This is not a free exercise problem.  This question has to do with Title VII (as quoted by bangzoom).  If this guy (<a href="http://www.worldnetdaily.com/news/article.asp?ARTICLE_ID=36484" target="_blank" class="postlink">http://www.worldnetdaily.com/news/article.asp?ARTICLE_ID=36484</a>) could be fired under title VII, I am afraid our pharmacist doesnt stand a chance.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
