				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Areadne wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I believe that you can refuse to hire someone of a specific religion if that religion prohibits the person from doing their job to full capacity.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
No, you can't.
<br />

<br />
What you CAN do is terminate the individual AFTER non-performance of the duty, regardless of what caused the non-performance (as long as it wasn't disability related).  As a matter of fact, any attempt to discern an prospective employee's religious affiliation is a big no-no.  While you may not act on the knowledge, if you knew about it beforehand, it can always be called into question if the person wants to file a discrimination suit.<br />_________________<br />Embar
