				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">IMNSHO he IS within his rights not to fill the perscription -- Himself.  However, he has a legal and ethical obligation based upon his oath and his job duties to see to it that this task falls to someone else -- he should contact someone else to deal with that scrip.  If he will not fill it and will not allow someone else to do so he needs to get his ass fired.
<br />

<br />
He has every right to say "I cannot do this", and still potentially keep his job so long as he finds a way to discharge his duties without breaking his personal ethics. Heck when she handed it to him he should have said "I can't fill this", and asked annother pharmacist to assist her. Hell, if he is the only one there he may be able to say, I cannot dispense this, please try pharmacy B down the street( his employer may have issues with that, but it is probably within reason.)
<br />

<br />
Once he obstructs her by saying I cant fill this, and I will not let you fill it then he has crossed the line.  He has an absolute right to, in the workplace, not do anything that he objects to on religious grounds, but he does not have the right to interfere with other employees fulfilling their duties, or to interfere with her ability to get the scrip filled somewhere.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
